# From Beanstalk source to a webpage

A compiler does not wake up and spit machine code at a file. It grows a program through a sequence of representations. Each stage sheds one kind of ambiguity and passes a clearer form to the next.

This series follows that growth for one small Beanstalk project. You already write Rust. You know functions, enums, structs and ownership as a user. You may not yet own the words *intermediate representation*, *link plan* or *borrow validation*. That is fine. Each term arrives when the running example needs it.

These pages teach. They do not define compiler behaviour. Accepted architecture lives in the canonical design documents. Current support lives in the progress matrix. Sequencing lives in the roadmap. When those disagree with an old habit in the code, the design document wins for this tour.

## The project you will carry

Keep this tree in your head for the whole series:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
compiler_walkthrough/
├── config.bst
└── src/
    ├── #page.bst
    └── greeting.bst
]

And keep these source shapes stable:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
-- greeting.bst

greeting_prefix #= "Hello"

greet |name String| -> String:
    return [: [greeting_prefix], [name]!]
;
]

[codeblock, $code("text"):
-- #page.bst

import @greeting { greet }

visitor = "Priya"

[$html:
    <p>[greet(visitor)]</p>
]
]

The final relevant fragment the series aims at:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
<p>Hello, Priya!</p>
]

Priya never changes. The file names never change. The fragment never changes. Side examples may branch away for a paragraph. They always return to this greeting.

## What each stage hands the next

One strip of checkpoints runs through every article:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
project tree
-> command and config
-> canonical source graph
-> located tokens
-> prepared shells
-> bound interfaces and ordered declarations
-> typed AST and semantic identities
-> folded constants, generated requests and TIR handoff
-> structured diagnostics
-> validated HIR
-> borrow and ownership side-table facts
-> immutable module artefacts and fingerprints
-> entry assembly and reachable function union
-> deterministic target assignment
-> JavaScript and Wasm outputs
-> HTML, runtime assets and output manifest
]

Each article opens with the incoming representation and closes with the outgoing one. If a page jumps ahead, you have left the chronological route.

**Diagram placeholder:** Growth path of compiler representations from project tree to HTML output

*Caption: simplified Beanstalk walkthrough, not a universal compiler taxonomy.*
*Question: which step still looks like source, and which first looks like a program a host can run?*

## Four owners you will meet again

**Build system.** Selects the command, discovers source, builds graphs, schedules modules, plans entries and owns writing files to disk.

**Compiler frontend and analysis.** Prepares syntax, binds interfaces, checks semantics, lowers HIR and validates access.

**Artefact builder.** Assembles selected compiler facts into an output plan for one kind of project, such as an HTML page.

**Target backends.** Lower validated functions and runtime needs into JavaScript, Wasm and glue.

A fact has one owner. Later stages consume that fact. They do not rebuild it from source text for sport.

